<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>IPCC 5th Assessment Review</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Professor Michael J Kelly FRS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">FREng</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> (IPC0013)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In 1868, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the economist </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">William Stanley Jevons FRS published ‘The Coal Question’.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  He was the Lord Stern PBA of his day.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">He</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> noted th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at Britain was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">addicted to coal.  His main message was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it should abandon the industrial revolution forthwith, as the future social collapse when the coal ran out (i.e. about now) would be too horrible to contemplate.  He was ignored</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and correctly so</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: alternatives to coal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">i.e. oil and gas) were discovered as were much greater reserves of coal.  Arguably the world is a much better place for most people today compared with their great-grandparents in terms of the adequacy and variety of food, the quality and warmth of homes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the access to healthcare, education and transport.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  The IPCC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is using the science in AR5 to make</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> similar claims today in the context of carbon dioxide emissions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> versus human progress</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as I now show.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The difference between living in 1800 and now is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that each person in a developed country now uses about </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">six</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-seven</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> times as much energy per person per day.  Indeed using the per capita consumption of energy in 1800 as a unit, today we use approximately one unit on personal mobility on land, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nearly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">another</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> unit on mobility by air and sea, and three units on the manufacture and distribution of all that we buy.  We still use a comparable amount of energy in heating a main room of our house, sourcing local produce and tools as we did 200 years ago.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Nearly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> this improvement in the living standards of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">seven times as many people on earth as in 1800 has been and continues to be possible </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the use of fossil fuels as the source of the extra energy.  Only of order 15% comes from biomass (i.e. using wood as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a fuel as throughout history</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, nuclear and hydropower</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a negligible (&lt;1%) amount from renewable energy.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">    Any recommendation to reduce carbon emissions by 80% without a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> readily available and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mature </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">non-carbon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">so</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">urce of energy is actually </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">more pe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rverse</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> now</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> than the recommendation of Jevons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in 1868</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The strength of the IPCC case that the world should severely curtail its carbon emissions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in short order</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should be tensioned against other practical considerations.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Empirical studies of the global</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> climate during the 20</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> century all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">suggest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> another century like the last and a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nother</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> temperature rise of order 1C.  It is only the computer models that produce the higher temperatures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the alarm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  In</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the IPCC’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ARC, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consensus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> rate of increase in temperature since 1950 has been revised down by a factor of two to a value of 0.1C/decade in agreement with the empirical results.  The computer models are acknowledged to have been predicting at least twice as much temperature rise as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> observed over the last 25 years, and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> they</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have not predicted the present </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">temperature </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">statis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> when the empirical models did, pointing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the repeated plateaux/falls starting in 1880, 1940 and now 2000.  If the present temperature </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">statis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> continues for anothe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r decade </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or more, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as the empirical models predict</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> then the climate models are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">demonstrably and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">seriously deficient as tools to predict the future.  Should another downward reduction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the rate of global warming</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be needed in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the near</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> future</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to accord with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> real-world data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the whole edifice of ‘unmanaged man-made’ climate change will be seen as a hollow scare as based on our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">limited </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">present scientific </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">understanding, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">potential downsides will be centuries away with ample time for technological fixes.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> In the terms of a ‘risk’ analysis, the amount we should be willing to pay in any form of insuranc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e premium should be coming down as a consequence of AR5.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> recent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2-day meeting at the Royal Society entitled ‘Next Steps in Climate Science – the nex</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t steps’ I got one of the key speakers Professor </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Jochem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Marotzke</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Germany</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to admit that he fully expected an upturn in the globally averaged temperature before 2020 on the basis of his models.  I was perturbed when </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cautioned that he was making himself a hostage to fortune.   In mainstream science that happens all the time, and it precisely the test of prediction against data that is the test of a theory.  The more general understanding is that most scientists w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ould query the integrity and fitness-for-purpose of all of the models if they continue to miss the present hiatus should it continue for a period of 25 years.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If we do spend trillions of pounds globally at redirecting human living and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">introduce </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a non-ca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rbon energy future, just what impact will it have on the future climate?  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Can we be sure that higher temperatures will actually be avoided?  If not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the money spent on mitigation as opposed to adaption</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> would have been largely wasted in terms of opportunit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ies foregone to improve the human condition.  Is the science able to reassure us that mitigation really is value for money?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">How sure are we that higher temperatures really will be as bad as made out?  The temperature rise to date has coincided with impr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ovements in the human condition.  How robust is the case that this will turn sour in the future?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Over geological times there have been wider excursions in temperature and we are in what is historically a cold but interglacial period now.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If after all t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he analysis, the elimination of carbon dioxide emissions must be accelerated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (a stage I am not convinced we have reached by any means)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, then we must tackle the challenge in a way that is likely to succeed, and not repeat the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nonsenses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of recent decades whi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ch manifestly are not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> succeeding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and will not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">succeed to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">do the job.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The rush, in response to the 1970s oil crises</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to install windmills and solar panels over square kilometres of the Mojave Desert </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in California </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the 1980s should be a lesson to us now</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">They can be seen by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">googling</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ‘abandoned windmills’ of ‘abandoned solar farms’.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Once subsidies stopped, they did not produce enough electricity to pay for the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> maintenance.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I am not persuaded that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the renewable tec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nologies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sufficiently more matur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e, robust and economic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">now than they were 30 years ago.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">10</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Renewable energy sources are intrinsically dilute at source.  One needs all 1000 square kilometres of the Fen Country (now producing food) to generate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">0.8-1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GW from biomass if we harvested and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">burned </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">miscanthus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a rapidly growing grass.  We already get 1.3GW from Sizewell B, the actual </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nuclear </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">plant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which is less than one tenth of a square kilometre in area.  The factor of 10,000 in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">energy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">efficiency of t